1. The primes hidden inside a wave spectrum

The key object again is the Riemann zeta function:

\zeta(s)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^s}

This function encodes all integers.

But the astonishing part is its Euler product, which shows primes are the fundamental building blocks:

\zeta(s)=\prod_{p \ \text{prime}} \frac{1}{1-p^{-s}}

Meaning:

integers = combinations of primes

Primes are the atoms of arithmetic.

⸻

2. Where the wave behavior appears

The mystery comes from the zeros of the zeta function.

These are values where:

\zeta(s)=0

They appear to lie along a vertical line in the complex plane.

Mathematicians call this the critical line.

The Riemann Hypothesis proposes that all important zeros satisfy:

\text{Re}(s)=\tfrac{1}{2}

Those zeros determine how primes are distributed.

⸻

